  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How? Ant walks from corner A (bottom left) of front wall to the other corner C (bottom right) of rear wall of a 3 meter cubical room. Shortest route?",
  "response": "To find the shortest path for the ant walking from corner A (the bottom left corner of the front wall) to corner C (the bottom right corner of the rear wall) in a 3-meter cube, we can visualize the cube and flatten it out as needed.\n\nLet's define the positions of the corners:\n\n- Corner A (0, 0, 0) - bottom left corner of the front wall\n- Corner C (3, 3, 0) - bottom right corner of the rear wall\n\nTo find the shortest path, we can \"unfold\" the cube. One useful way is to consider two adjacent walls along with the floor. When the cube is unfolded properly, the ant walks from A to C along a flat surface.\n\nOne effective unfolding is to lay the back wall and the floor flat. In this case, the ant would travel from A (0, 0) to C (3, 3) where the y-coordinate represents the height of the wall (3), and x-coordinate represents the horizontal distance (3). \n\nIf we unfold the wall that is opposite A to include the bottom of the room, this describes a rectangle shape:\n\n1. From (0, 0) on the flat surface (bottom wall)\n2. The opposite corner will be at (3, 3) as both the back wall and the height is covered.\n\nThe shortest distance between these two points (A and C) is the straight line in the Cartesian plane, which can be calculated using the distance formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Distance} = \\sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}\n\\]\n\nSo, substituting for points A (0,0) and C (3,3):\n\n\\[\n\\text{Distance} = \\sqrt{(3 - 0)^2 + (3 - 0)^2} = \\sqrt{9 + 9} = \\sqrt{18} = 3\\sqrt{2} \\text{ meters.}\n\\]\n\nThus, the shortest route for the ant from corner A to corner C is \\( 3\\sqrt{2} \\) meters.",
